      "testConditions": {
        "en": "(i) Test animals: Select healthy albino rats weigh-ing between 55 and 180 g, fasted for 24 hours before the test but allowed to drink water ad libitum. Standard solutions: Dissolve a quantity of Calcitonin Salmon RS in acetic acid buffer solution containing 0.1z bovine serum albumin, and prepare a high-dose standard solution SH and a low-dose standard solution SL containing exactly 0.050 and 0.025 Units per mL, respectively. Sample solutions: According to the labeled units, Ya ＝ －Y1 － Y2 ＋ Y3 ＋ Y4 Yb ＝ Y1 － Y2 ＋ Y3 － Y4 a: Amount (mg) of Calcitonin Salmon taken b: Total volume (mL) of the high-dose sample solution prepared by dissolving Calcitonin Salmon in acetic acid buffer solution containing 0.1z bovine serum albumin. c: Peptide content (z) F? computed by the following equation should be smaller than F1 shown in the table against n with which s2 is calcu-lated. Calculate L (P ＝ 0.95) by use of the following equa-tion: L should be not more than 0.20. If F? exceeds F1, or if L exceeds 0.20, repeat the test, increasing the number of animals or arranging the assay conditions so that F? is not more than F1 and L is not more than 0.20. F? ＝ (－Y1 ＋ Y2 ＋ Y3 － Y4)2/4fs2 f: Number of the test animals of each group. s 2 ＝ {Sy2 － (Y/f )}/n Sy2: The sum of squares of y1, y2, y3 and y4 in each group. Y ＝ Y 2 ＋ Y2 ＋ Y 2 ＋ Y 2 1 2 3 4 weigh accurately a suitable amount of Calcitonin Salmon, and dissolve in acetic acid buffer solution containing 0.1z bovine serum albumin, and prepare a high-dose sample solu- n ＝ 4( f － 1) (C － 1)(CM 2 ＋ 0.09062) L ＝ 2 C ＝ Y 2/(Y 2 － 4fs2t2) b b tion TH and the low-dose sample solution TL having Units equal to the standard solutions in equal volumes, respec-tively. Dose for injection: Inject 0.3 mL per animal. Procedure: Divide the test animals at random into 4 groups, A, B, C and D, with not less than 8 animals and equal numbers in each group. Inject SH, SL, TH and TL into the tail vein or subcutaneously into the neck of each animal of the respective groups. At 1 hour after the injection, collect blood from the abdominal aorta in a way that minimizes the suffering of the animals, allow the blood samples to stand t2: Value shown in the following table against n used to calculate s2. ‌594‌ n t2 ＝ F1 n t2 ＝ F1 n t2 ＝ F1 as directed under Flame Coloration Test <1.04> (1): no green color appears. 161.45 4.667 4.242 (4) Magnesium and alkali metals—Dissolve 1.0 g of 18.51 4.600 4.225 Precipitated Calcium Carbonate in a mixture of 20 mL of 10.129 4.543 4.210 water and 10 mL of dilute hydrochloric acid, boil, neutralize 7.709 4.494 4.196 with ammonia TS, and add ammonium oxalate TS until 6.608 4.451 4.183 precipitation of calcium oxalate is completed. Heat the mix- 5.987 4.414 4.171 ture on a water bath for 1 hour, cool, dilute with water to 5.591 4.381 4.085 100 mL, shake well, and filter. To 50 mL of the filtrate add 5.318 4.351 4.001 0.5 mL of sulfuric acid, evaporate to dryness, and ignite at 5.117 4.325 3.920 6009C to constant mass: the mass of the residue is not more 4.965 4.301 ∞ 3.841 than 5.0 mg. 11 4.844 12 4.747 23 4.279 24 4.260 (5) Arsenic <1.11>—Moisten 0.40 g of Precipitated Cal-cium Carbonate with 1 mL of water, then dissolve in 4 mL of dilute hydrochloric acid, use this solution as the test solu-"
